<h3 id=3D"CommunicationTheory-=E2=9C=85Summary.3">=E2=9C=85 <strong>Summary=
</strong></h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Digital modulation</strong> encodes digital data on a carrier us=
ing <strong>amplitude, frequency, phase, or combination</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>ASK:</strong> Simple but noise-prone</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>FSK:</strong> Frequency-based, moderate robustness</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>PSK:</strong> Phase-based, robust</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>QAM:</strong> Combines amplitude and phase, high spectral effici=
ency</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>OFDM:</strong> Parallel multi-carrier, modern wireless systems</=
p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<p>I can create a <strong>diagram showing carrier signals for ASK, FSK, BPS=
K, QPSK, and QAM</strong> for a visual comparison of digital modulation sch=
emes.</p>
<p>Do you want me to create that diagram?</p>
<p></p>
<p></p>
<ol start=3D"5">
<li>
<p>Pulse and digital signals: pulse amplitude modulation (PAM), pulse code =
modulation (PCM), delta modulation (DM), adaptive delta modulation (ADM);</=
p></li>
</ol>
<p>Here=E2=80=99s a <strong>concise and structured overview</strong> of <st=
rong>Pulse and Digital Modulation Techniques</strong>:</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"CommunicationTheory-1=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3Introduction.3"><strong>1=
=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Introduction</strong></h2>
<p><strong>Pulse modulation</strong> is a method of <strong>encoding analog=
 signals into pulse signals</strong> for transmission.</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Converts <strong>continuous-time signals</strong> into <strong>discrete-=
time signals</strong>.</p></li>
<li>
<p>Enables <strong>digital communication, noise immunity, and multiplexing<=
/strong>.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"CommunicationTheory-2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3PulseAmplitudeModulation(P=
AM)"><strong>2=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Pulse Amplitude Modulation (PAM)</strong><=
/h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Concept:</strong> Analog signal <strong>sampled at regular inter=
vals</strong>; <strong>amplitude of each pulse</strong> proportional to the=
 signal at that instant.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Characteristics:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Simple but <strong>susceptible to noise</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>Basis for <strong>PCM and other digital schemes</strong></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong> Baseband transmission, analog to digital =
conversion</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"CommunicationTheory-3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3PulseCodeModulation(PCM)">=
<strong>3=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Pulse Code Modulation (PCM)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Concept:</strong> Analog signal =E2=86=92 sampled =E2=86=92 <str=
ong>quantized</strong> =E2=86=92 converted to <strong>binary code</strong><=
/p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Steps:</strong></p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p><strong>Sampling:</strong> At Nyquist rate</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Quantization:</strong> Round samples to nearest level</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Encoding:</strong> Convert quantized value to binary code</p></l=
i>
</ol></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Noise-resistant</p></li>
<li>
<p>Digital transmission possible</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong> Telephony, digital audio (CDs), digital T=
V</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"CommunicationTheory-4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3DeltaModulation(DM)"><stro=
ng>4=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Delta Modulation (DM)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Concept:</strong> Transmit only <strong>difference between succe=
ssive samples</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Characteristics:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Simple implementation</p></li>
<li>
<p>Uses <strong>1-bit code per sample</strong> (up/down)</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Drawbacks:</strong> Slope overload, granular noise</p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong> Voice transmission, low-bit-rate systems<=
/p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"CommunicationTheory-5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3AdaptiveDeltaModulation(AD=
M/ADPCM)"><strong>5=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Adaptive Delta Modulation (ADM / ADPC=
M)</strong></h2>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Improvement over DM:</strong> Step size <strong>adapts to signal=
 slope</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Advantages:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>Reduces <strong>slope overload and granular noise</strong></p></li>
<li>
<p>More efficient for <strong>wide dynamic range signals</strong></p></li>
</ul></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Applications:</strong> Mobile telephony, voice over IP (VoIP)</p=
></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"CommunicationTheory-6=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3SummaryTable.1"><strong>6=
=EF=B8=8F=E2=83=A3 Summary Table</strong></h2>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
